class Solution {
      
    // Finds index of the largest element
    int largest(int arr[], int n){
        int max = 0;                    // local variable (safe for multiple TCs)
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            if(arr[i] > arr[max])
                max = i;
        }
        return max;                     // returns index of largest
    }
    
    public int getSecondLargest(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        if(n < 2) return -1;            // edge case: not enough elements
        
        int max = largest(arr,n);       // index of largest
        int smax = -1;                  // index of second largest
        
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            // KEY FIX: ensures second largest is strictly smaller than largest
            if(arr[i] < arr[max]){
                if(smax == -1)          // first valid candidate
                    smax = i;
                else if(arr[i] > arr[smax])
                    smax = i;           // better second largest found
            }
        }
        
        if(smax == -1) return -1;       // all elements equal
        return arr[smax];               // return value, not index
    }
}


////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Second Largest:
Given an array of positive integers arr[], return the second largest element from the array. If the second largest element doesn't exist then return -1.

Note: The second largest element should not be equal to the largest element.

Examples:

Input: arr[] = [12, 35, 1, 10, 34, 1]
Output: 34
Explanation: The largest element of the array is 35 and the second largest element is 34.

Input: arr[] = [10, 5, 10]
Output: 5
Explanation: The largest element of the array is 10 and the second largest element is 5.

Input: arr[] = [10, 10, 10]
Output: -1
Explanation: The largest element of the array is 10 and the second largest element does not exist.

Constraints:
2 ≤ arr.size() ≤ 105
1 ≤ arr[i] ≤ 105
